'''Sir Robert William''' &quot;'''Bobby'''&quot; '''Robson''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (18 February 1933&amp;nbsp;– 31 July 2009)&lt;ref name=&quot;bbcdeath&quot;&gt;{{cite news | title = Football legend Robson dies at 76 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8177945.stm | publisher=news.bbc.co.uk | date = 31 July 2009 | accessdate =31 July 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; was an English [[Association football|footballer]] and manager, who coached seven European clubs and the [[England national football team|England national team]] during his career.

His professional playing career as an [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|inside-forward]] spanned nearly 20 years, during which he played for three clubs: [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], and, briefly, [[Vancouver Royals|Vancouver]]. He also made 20 appearances for England, scoring four goals.

After his playing career he found success as both a club and international manager, winning league championships in both the [[Netherlands]] and [[Portugal]], earning trophies in England and Spain, and taking England to the semi-final of the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]]. His last management role was as a mentor to the manager of the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Irish national football team]].

Robson was created a [[Knight Bachelor]] in 2002, was inducted as a member of the [[English Football Hall of Fame]] in 2003, and was the honorary president of [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]. From 1991 onwards he suffered recurrent medical problems with cancer, and in March 2008, put his name and efforts into the [[Sir Bobby Robson Foundation]], a cancer research charity. In August 2008, his lung cancer was confirmed to be terminal; he said: &quot;My condition is described as static and has not altered since my last bout of [[chemotherapy]]...I am going to die sooner rather than later. But then everyone has to go sometime and I have enjoyed every minute&quot;. He died just under a year later.

== Early life ==
Born in [[Sacriston]], County Durham, Robson was the fourth of five sons of Philip and Lilian Robson (née Watt).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | first = Bobby
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | publisher=[[Hodder &amp; Stoughton]]
 | year = 2005
 | pages = 6
 | chapter = Going underground
 | isbn = 0-340-82346-1 }}&lt;/ref&gt; When he was a few months old, Robson's family moved to the nearby village of [[Langley Park, County Durham|Langley Park]] where his father was a coal miner. As a boy, he was often taken by his father to watch [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] at [[St James' Park]], requiring a bus ride or a walk of several miles.&lt;ref name=&quot;mail on sunday&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Dream to manage Newcastle&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/news/432906.stm
|title=Robson: Dream to manage Newcastle
|publisher=BBC Sport
|accessdate=13 June 2007
|date=30 September 1999}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 15
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Robson describes [[Jackie Milburn]] and [[Len Shackleton]] as his childhood heroes.&lt;ref name=&quot;Dream to manage Newcastle&quot;/&gt; Both played for Newcastle in the inside-forward position, the position Robson would later assume during his playing career.

Robson attended Waterhouses Secondary Modern School but the headmaster did not allow the school football team to join a league.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/columnists/backtrack/3695160.Three_Tuns_reunite_with_tons_of_happy_memories/ Three Tuns reunite with tons of happy memories]&quot;. ''The Northern Echo'' 2008-09-23. Retrieved on 2 April 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; Instead, he began to play for Langley Park Juniors on Saturday mornings at the age of eleven, and by the time he was 15, he was representing the club at Under-18 level.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 8
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Robson played football whenever he possibly could but also worked as an electrician's apprentice for the [[National Coal Board]] in the Langley Park [[colliery]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 1
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; In May 1950, [[Bill Dodgin, Sr.|Bill Dodgin]], the [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] manager made a personal visit to the Robson household to offer Bobby a professional contract. Despite being offered a contract by nearby [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], the offer made by Dodgin was too attractive to turn down, so he signed for Fulham and moved to London,&lt;ref name=espn/&gt;&lt;ref name=p1819&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | pages = 18–19
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=nufc&gt;{{Cite web
| url = http://www.nufc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/ManagersDetail/0,,10278~560999,00.html
| title = Newcastle United F.C. History&amp;nbsp;— Bobby Robson
| accessdate =30 August 2007
| publisher=Newcastle United F.C.
}}&lt;/ref&gt; playing as a wing-half and inside-forward.&lt;ref name=tenfacts/&gt;  Robson had also interested his beloved Newcastle, but he opted to join Fulham as, in his opinion, &quot;Newcastle made no appreciable effort to secure [my] signature&quot;.

== Playing care
Although Robson had signed professionally, his father insisted he continue to work as an electrician. He spent the day working at the [[Fest
 | pages = 20
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Eventually this took its toll on Robson and he gave up his trade for full-time football.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 21
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Robson made his debut in 1950 for Fulham, recently promoted to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]], in a match against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Robson&quot;&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 24
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; He came to regard Fulham as &quot;a nice club, a social club...&quot; but &quot;never...a serious, championship-challenging club&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 25, p28
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Indeed, he and Fulham were relegated from the top-flight in the [[1951-52 in English football|1951–52]] season,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?teamid=1055&amp;seasonid=81
| title = Final 1951/1952 English Division 1 (old) Table
| publisher=Soccerbase
| accessdate =16 May 2007
}}&lt;/ref&gt; but he made his return to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]], four years later, when he signed for [[Vic Buckingham]]'s [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in March 1956.&lt;ref name=espn&gt;{{Cite web
| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/manager?id=31
| title = Sir Bobby Robson
| publisher=ESPN
| accessdate =15 May 2007
}}&lt;/ref&gt; The transfer fee of £25,000 was a club record for Albion at the time.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 29
 | chapter = Tales From The Riverbank
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Matthews
 | first = Tony
 | coauthors=Mackenzie, Colin
 | title = Albion! A Complete Record of West Bromwich Albion 1879–1987
 | publisher=Breedon Books
 | year = 1987
 | pages = 294
 | isbn = 0-907969-23-2
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

He made his Albion debut in a 4–0 home defeat by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 10 March 1956.&lt;ref name=&quot;WBA Whos Who&quot;&gt;{{cite book | last = Matthews | first = Tony | title = The Who's Who of West Bromwich Albion | publisher=Breedon Books | year = 2005 | pages = 202–203 | isbn = 1-85983-474-4}}&lt;/ref&gt; In [[1957-58 in English football|1957–58]] he was the club's top league goalscorer; his tally of 24 goals included four in a 5–1 win against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | last=Matthews | first=Tony | title=West Bromwich Albion: The Complete Record | publisher=Breedon Books | year=2007 | pages = 172 &amp; 292 |  isbn=978-1-85983-565-4}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[[Ronnie Allen]] was the club's top scorer overall, with 28 goals.&lt;/ref&gt; He went on to play 257 games and score 61 goals for West Bromwich Albion and captained the team for the [[1960-61 in English football|1960–61]] and [[1961-62 in English football|1961–62]] seasons.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
| last=McOwan
| first=Gavin
| title=The Essential History of West Bromwich Albion
| publisher=Headline | year=2002 |pages=252–253
| isbn=0-7553-1146-9 }}&lt;/ref&gt; In August 1962, however, he returned to Fulham after a disagreement with Albion vice-chairman Jim Gaunt over his salary.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 39
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Robson states Gaunt was chairman at the time, however he was vice-chairman until 1963.&lt;/ref&gt; The on-going dispute over both minimum and maximum wages in the game, instigated by Robson's team-mate [[Jimmy Hill]] and the [[Professional Footballers' Association]], combined with the birth of Robson's second son, prompted Robson to demand a higher salary.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 39–40
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Gaunt refused to negotiate Robson's contract, so Robson placed a transfer request and was sold to Fulham for £20,000 in a deal which doubled his salary.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 40
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Soon after Robson joined Fulham, the club sold [[Alan Mullery]] and [[Rodney Marsh (footballer)|Rodney Marsh]], meaning Robson's chances of securing any significant honour there were substantially reduced.&lt;ref name=nowin&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 43
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Robson himself stated &quot;In all my time as a footballer, I didn't win a thing.&quot;&lt;ref name=nowin/&gt;

Despite press reports of interest from [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 44
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the offer of a [[player-manager]] role by [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 61
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Robson left Fulham in 1967 and accepted a three-year deal with Canada's [[Vancouver Royals]]. He was to be player-manager in their inaugural 1968 season in the [[North American Soccer League (1968–1984)|North American Soccer League]] and believed it &quot;...was a chance too good to miss&quot;.&lt;ref name=espn/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 62
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; The position proved difficult; a long-distance joint-ownership agreement gave the Hungarian footballer [[Ferenc Puskás]] control over the [[San Francisco]] section of the squad,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | last =  Jukich
 | first = Roy
 | title = Puskas Wins Soccer Derby
 | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pJZlAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=vooNAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=969,81414&amp;dq=bobby+robson+three-year+contract&amp;hl=en
 |work=The Vancouver Sun | date = 16 January 1968
 | accessdate =12 February 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt; while Robson took care of the Vancouver squad. Robson was dissatisfied by this situation and when, in January 1968, Fulham offered him a contract as their manager, he accepted the position at [[Craven Cottage]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 64–65
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== International playing career ===
During his first spell at Fulham, Robson participated in two ambassadorial Football Association tours in the [[Caribbean|West Indies]] in 1955 and South Africa in 1956.&lt;ref name=&quot;Robson&quot; /&gt;  However, it was during his time at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] that he graduated to the full England squad, with his first call-up in 1956. His manager, Vic Buckingham, advocated the &quot;[[push and run]]&quot; approach to the game, a precursor to &quot;[[total football]]&quot;,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 31
 | chapter = La-di-dah
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; and playing this, Robson graduated to the full [[England national football team|England]] squad in 1956,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 33
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;  It was also at West Bromwich Albion that Robson met future England international and assistant coach [[Don Howe]].&lt;ref name=p33to35&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 33–35
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

He went on to make 20 appearances for the [[England national football team|England national team]], making his debut in a November 1957 victory against [[France national football team|France]], scoring twice in a 4–0 victory.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web
| url = http://www.nufc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/ManagersDetail/0,,10278~560999,00.html
| title = Managers&amp;nbsp;— Sir Bobby Robson
| publisher=Newcastle United F.C.
| accessdate =16 May 2007
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Although he made a successful debut, he was dropped for England's next game against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], in favour of [[Bobby Charlton]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 48–49
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; He was, however, selected for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958 World Cup]] squad, ahead of [[Nat Lofthouse]] and [[Stanley Matthews]] but returned from Sweden disappointed, as England were defeated by the [[USSR national football team|Soviet Union]] in a group play-off match.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 53
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Following the [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958 World Cup]], Robson became an established member of the England squad, enjoying considerable success in a period between October 1960 and March 1961 when he played in six England victories, including scoring a goal in the record 9–3 defeat of Scotland at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 54
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; He was selected for the [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962 World Cup finals]] in Chile but an injury to his ankle sustained in a pre-tournament friendly against a Chilean club side ruled him out of most of the tournament. As Robson recalled, &quot;I never played for England again...my international career was unfulfilled&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 58–60
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

