== Death ==
On 31 July 2009, Robson died of lung cancer at his home in County Durham,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=Jonathan Stewart |url=http://www.4ni.co.uk/northern_ireland_news.asp?id=97315 |title=Football legend Sir Bobby Robson dies |publisher=4ni.co.uk |accessdate=31 July 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; aged 76, after a long battle with the disease.&lt;ref name=&quot;bbcdeath&quot;/&gt; After the news of his death, leading figures from the world of football and politics paid tribute to him. [[Manchester United]] manager [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] called him a &quot;great friend, a wonderful individual and tremendous football man.&quot; UEFA president [[Michel Platini]] said: &quot;He will be remembered not only for his playing career and his outstanding managerial career at both club and international level, but also because he was a truly warm and passionate human being.&quot; [[Gary Lineker]] said: &quot;It is a sad day and a great loss. He was a wonderful man and will be deeply missed by everybody in the country. I never played for a more enthusiastic man. He gave so much to the game.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8177945.stm | title= Legend Sir Bobby Robson, 76, dies |work=BBC News  | date=31 July 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Former Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, [[Tony Blair]], described Sir Bobby as a &quot;real Geordie gentleman.&quot;&lt;ref name=Tributes&gt;{{cite news
 | title = Football honours Sir Bobby Robson
 |publisher=bbc.co.uk
 | date = 31 July 2009
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8178079.stm
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; According to the then Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]], Robson &quot;epitomised everything that is great about football in this country.&quot;&lt;ref name=Tributes/&gt; His friend, the broadcaster [[Michael Parkinson]], said: &quot;Robson will be remembered long after the present lot are old bones. By his decency, his humour, his love of the game's traditions and origins and confusion at what it had become, he made present day football look what it is – shabby by comparison. I can think of no more fitting epitaph.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url= http://www.michaelparkinson.tv/week-in-words,bobby-robson_137.htm | title= Bobby Robson}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Robson's funeral, a private family ceremony, took place on 5 August 2009. The location remained undisclosed at the request of his family until the funeral had taken place. It was later revealed to be [[Esh, County Durham]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Funeral&quot;&gt;
{{cite news
   |title=Sir Bobby laid to rest near where he grew up
   |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-evening-chronicle/2009/08/06/i-wanted-something-to-last-forever-a-tribute-i-can-take-to-the-grave-72703-24332832/
   |date=6 August 2009
   |accessdate=6 August 2009
   |publisher=Newcastle Evening Chronicle}}&lt;/ref&gt; A thanksgiving service for Robson was held on 21 September 2009 at [[Durham Cathedral]]. One thousand invited guests attended the service, which was also broadcast live on national television, and to Newcastle United's [[St James' Park]], Ipswich Town's [[Portman Road]] ground, and Fulham's [[Craven Cottage]].&lt;ref name=Guardian21Sep09Memorial&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/sep/21/sir-bobby-robson-memorial-service2
|title=Sir Bobby Robson's memorial service: football figures assemble in Durham
|work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=21 September 2009
|accessdate=22 September 2009
| first=Paul
| last=Hayward
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Honours ==
Bobby Robson was awarded a number of honours for his contributions to football. In 1990, at the end of his eight-year reign as England manager, he was awarded a [[CBE]] and in 2002, he was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]]; both awards were for services to football.&lt;ref name=&quot;honours autobiography&quot;&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 297
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name = &quot;BBC-Kanighits&quot;&gt;{{cite news
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2499521.stm
 |publisher=BBC News
 | date = 21 November 2002
 | accessdate =16 August 2007
 | title = Sir Bobby Robson receives knighthood
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2002 (during his time as Newcastle manager), the 69-year-old Robson was awarded the [[Freedom of the city|freedom]] of [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] and the [[UEFA]] President's Award for 'services to football'.&lt;ref name=nufc/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;WBA Whos Who&quot;/&gt;  He was inducted into the [[English Football Hall of Fame]] in 2003 in recognition of his impact as a manager.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web
 | url = http://www.nationalfootballmuseum.com/pages/fame/Inductees/bobbyrobson.htm
 | title = English Football Hall of Fame Profile
 | publisher=[[National Football Museum]]
 | accessdate =13 May 2007
}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; Following his time as Newcastle United manager in 2005, Robson was made an Honorary Freeman of Newcastle,&lt;ref name=free/&gt; which, in his autobiography, he described as being &quot;the proudest moment of my life&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book
 | last = Robson
 | title = Farewell but Not Goodbye
 | pages = 294
 | chapter = Hello and goodbye
 | isbn = 0-340-84064-1
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Robson also won the 1992&amp;nbsp;Football Writers' Association Tribute Award for an outstanding contribution to the national game,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web
 | url = http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamHons/HonsFWATribute.html
 | title = England Honours&amp;nbsp;— Football Writers' Association Tribute Award
 | accessdate =16 August 2007
 | publisher=Englandfootballonline.com
}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the 2001 British Sports Writers' Association Pat Besford Trophy for Outstanding Achievement.&lt;ref name = &quot;BBC-Kanighits&quot;/&gt; In 2005 he received a lifetime achievement award from the Sports Coach UK Awards,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/front_page/4508254.stm
 | title = Fletcher honoured with top award
 | accessdate =31 August 2007
 | date = 7 December 2005
 |publisher=BBC Sport
}}&lt;/ref&gt; and was also awarded the Eircom International Personality of the Year in 2006.&lt;ref name=&quot;honours autobiography&quot;/&gt; On 9 December 2007, Robson was awarded the [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year Lifetime Achievement Award|Lifetime Achievement Award]] at the [[BBC]]'s [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year|Sports Personality of the Year]] show in recognition of &quot;his contribution as both player and manager in a career spanning more than half a century&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/sports_personality_of_the_year/7134846.stm
 | title = Robson wins BBC achievement award
 | accessdate =8 December 2007
 | date = 8 December 2007
 |publisher=BBC Sport
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On 5 May 2008, during the 30th anniversary celebrations of [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]'s 1978 FA Cup win, Robson was granted the Freedom of [[Ipswich]] by the Lady Mayor.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/suffolk/7384954.stm
 | title = Sir Bobby given freedom of town
 | date = 6 May 2008
 | accessdate =21 June 2008
 |publisher=BBC News }}&lt;/ref&gt; On 8 December 2008, he earned another such accolade when he was given the Freedom of the [[Durham|City of Durham]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/7770684.stm
 | title = Sir Bobby to become city Freeman
 | date = 8 December 2008
 | accessdate =8 December 2008
 |publisher=BBC News
}}&lt;/ref&gt; In March 2009, [[UEFA]] awarded Robson the Emerald UEFA Order of Merit award, awarded to &quot;individuals who have dedicated their talents to the good of the game&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 | url = http://www.uefa.com/uefa/aboutuefa/organisation/congress/news/newsid=813078.html
 | title = UEFA tribute to loyal football servants
 | date = 24 March 2009
 | accessdate =20 September 2010
 | publisher=UEFA
 | first = Mark
 | last = Chaplin
}}&lt;/ref&gt; The award was presented to Sir Bobby at [[St James' Park]] on 26 July 2009, prior to the [[Sir Bobby Robson Trophy match]], and just five days before his death.&lt;ref name=NorthernEcho26Jul09/&gt;

=== Posthumous honours ===
In December 2009 Robson was posthumously awarded the [[FIFA Fair Play Award]], for the &quot;gentlemanly qualities he showed throughout his career as a player and coach&quot;.&lt;ref name=FIFA21Dec2009&gt;{{cite press release
|url=http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/awards/gala/news/newsid=1149850.html
|title=Fair Play Award honours Robson
|publisher=FIFA
|date=21 December 2009
|accessdate=29 March 2011
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xXyOHsd7
|archivedate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[The Football League]] gave Newcastle United and Ipswich Town special dispensation to wear special commemorative kits for their [[Football League Championship|Championship]] match on 26 September 2009 at Portman Road, in aid of Sir Bobby's Foundation.  At half-time during this match, the North Stand of Portman Road was renamed the Sir Bobby Robson Stand.&lt;ref name=BBC18Sep09&gt;{{cite news
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/8263229.stm
 | title = League allows Robson tribute kits
 |publisher=BBC Sport
 | date =18 September 2009
 | accessdate =20 September 2009
 | archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5jvYTfOAz
 | archivedate = 20 September 2009
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=BBC2Nov2009Shirts&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/8337473.stm
|title=Sir Bobby shirts raise thousands
|publisher=BBC News
|date=2 November 2009
|accessdate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=BBC13Jan2010ShirtSales&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/8456703.stm
|title=Sir Bobby Newcastle shirt sales aid teenage cancer unit
|publisher=BBC News
|date=13 January 2010
|accessdate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1207417/Ipswich-unveil-Sir-Bobby-Robson-Stand-Town-beloved-Newcastle-United.html | work = Daily Mail | location = London | accessdate =20 October 2011 | date = 18 August 2009 | title = Ipswich to unveil 'Sir Bobby Robson Stand' when Town take on his beloved Newcastle United}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The first anniversary of Robson's death on 31 July 2010 was marked with a ceremony and pre-season [[friendly match]] at Newcastle's [[St James' Park]], between two of his former clubs Newcastle United and PSV Eindhoven, involving Robson's PSV captain [[Stan Valckx]] presenting a PSV shirt to the club.&lt;ref name=BBC&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-10826983
|title=Sir Bobby remembered one year on since his death
|publisher=BBC News
|date=31 July 2010
|accessdate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In July 2010 plans were unveiled for a memorial garden to Robson to be built in Newcastle. It was to be created by the city council in partnership with the regeneration company NE1Ltd, and located on [[Newcastle upon Tyne City Centre#Gallowgate|Gallowgate]] street close to the Newcastle United stadium [[St James' Park]]. Work began on the site in November 2010, with an expected completion of Spring 2011. The garden is to cover 400 square meters, and feature a tiered seating area and sculpted stone plinths reflecting aspects of his life and work. The area is also to host a 400 square metre memorial garden to [[Sir Bobby Robson]], with work beginning in November 2010, to be opened in Spring 2011.&lt;ref name=BBC26Jul2010GardenPlans&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-10764591
|title=Sir Bobby Robson's Tyneside garden tribute
|publisher=BBC News
|date=26 July 2010
|accessdate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=BBC22Nov2010GardenCommences&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-11810343
|title=Work starts on a memorial garden to Sir Bobby Robson
|publisher=BBC News
|date=22 November 2010
|accessdate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

With a keen interest in cricket as well as football, Robson was to have replaced [[Mike Gatting]] as President of the [[Lord's Taverners]] charity and cricket club in 2007, but this was prevented by his ill-health. After his death, the club held a dinner in his honour, as the &quot;The best President we never had&quot;.&lt;ref name=SBRFoundationBlog30Mar2010Dinner&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://sirbobbyrobsonfoundation.blogspot.com/2010/03/tribute-to-best-president-we-never-had.html
|title=Tribute To &quot;The Best President We Never Had&quot;
|date=30 March 2010
|accessdate=29 March 2011
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xY5vYYT8
|archivedate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In March 2011, the [[East Coast (train operating company)|East Coast train operating company]] [[nameplate|named]] one of its [[British Rail Class 91|Class 91]] electric locomotives ''Sir Bobby Robson'', unveiled at [[Newcastle Central Station]] by his widow Elsie and [[Alan Shearer]].&lt;ref name=BBC29Mar2011Train&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-12890755
|title=Sir Bobby Robson name given to train
|publisher=BBC News
|date=29 March 2011
|accessdate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=EastCoastTrains29Mar2011&gt;{{cite press release
|url=http://www.eastcoast.co.uk/about-us/Press-Release/2011/EAST-COAST-NAMES-TRAIN-SIR-BOBBY-ROBSON/
|title=East Coast Names Train Sir Bobby Robson
|publisher=East Coast Main Line Company
|date=29 March 2011
|accessdate=29 March 2011
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xXxVrMou
|archivedate=29 March 2011
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Similarly, in December 2011, the [[Port of Tyne]] Authority named its new work boat the ''Sir Bobby Robson''.&lt;ref name=portoftyne&gt;{{cite press release
|url=http://www.portoftyne.co.uk/news/port-of-tyne/new-boat-and-new-jobs-at-the-port-of-tyne/
|title=New Boat and New Jobs at the Port of Tyne
|publisher=Port of Tyne
|date=01 March 2012
|accessdate=01 March 2012
|archiveurl=
|archivedate=
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

